>>
Well, I'll vote against it twice. P-Notes haven't had a fair run.
<<

That's a statement I don't understand. P-notes have been around since
I first registered (not that this was soo long ago, but anyway).

>>
We're never going to have any kind of economy
around here if we are not willing to have to pay for things.
<<

But we _do_ have a working economy already! Indulgences work, and so
do VTs, with the only problem being inflation (but fighting inflation
is not a problem connected with implementing an economy, but with
running one - we're already doing that!).

I'd like to post a few remarks I made in a private mail some time ago:

>> 
[..] Actually, I consider myself one of the proponents of a real
economy. But I'd like to see a _real_ one, where the currencies, and
dealing with them, make real sense and not just lots of red tape.

VTs are good in that sense, because they are needed to do something
which is vital in a nomic: vote. Indulgences also are good, because
blots prevent you from doing something else which is important for a
nomic: winning. If you collect too many of them, you can even be
deregistered. 

P-notes, however, are a matter of red tape only, at least at the
moment: What is really the effect of using them? Or what is bad about
not having them? Nothing.

You can make as many proposals as you like without ever paying a
P-note. You will even be listed as author of the resulting rule
changes. The only _real_ effect P-notes can possibly have is that you
incur persistent debt penalties if you have a negative amount of
them. Great. 

As soon as someone introduces a usage for P-notes that makes them as
relevant as VTs and indulgences, I'll wholeheartedly support their
reintroduction. But at the moment they don't serve any purpose
whatsoever, and I proposed their abolition not out of a specific
dislike for P-notes but simply because several players had noted
recently, and were right in doing so, that the Agora rule set is
getting longer and more complex all the time without gaining a
corresponding amount of play complexity or increased fun. So I
thought, why carry around a concept that is functionless at the moment,
just in the hope that someone, someday will invent a good use for it?
Once this someone has eir idea, we can always reintroduce P-notes in a
single proposal, and this proposal will certainly get my FOR-vote.
<<

Of course, abolishing disinterested proposals instead of P-notes might
be a way to make P-notes functional again. While I would prefer the
simplification of abolishing P-notes altogether, the abolition of
disinterested proposals might be enough. 

Kolja A.

