One of the things that gives value to indulgences is the risk of being
deregistered for lawlessness. However, in typical Agora manner (I hope
I'm not hurting anyone's feelings here) at the moment we are
collectively ignoring this.

Kinda reminds me of the way we played Monopoly as kids: we couldn't
bear seeing each other going bancrupt, so we kept bailing each other
out with donations and loans. Later we realized that this wasn't
really the point of the game, so we made a "house rule" that
prohibited all donations and loans between players. Instead we allowed
players to borrow from the bank...

Of course, _real_ Monopoly it still wasn't; and I'm not arguing that
we should deregister anyone for lawlessness now (at least, that seems
to be the quiet consensus), but I don't like the present situation,
either, and would like to suggest the following amnesty proto:

##
When this proposal is adopted, the chancellor shall pay out 30
indulgences to all players with 20 or more blots.
##

Is this legal? Working? Better than announcing the lawlessness of
players in public? And: how are we ever going to get an economy
running if we ignore its negative effects on individual players (not
only deregistration, as in this case, but also simple inability to act
due to lack of funds)?

Kolja A.

