Laurent Bossavit wrote:
>
>> As I think it is beyond reasonable doubt that Morendil violated rule
>> 1729, I hereby judge this statement to be TRUE.
>
>I hereby call for the Appeal of this Judgement, on the grounds that
>it has not clearly be shown that the wording of Rule 1729 is such
>that it is possible, but illegal, to cast Votes in a manner not
>consistent with its strictures, whereas at the same time it seems to
>be customary to treat Rules such as the late 1741 as making it 
>impossible, rather than illegal, to cast Votes in a manner other than 
>prescribed therein.

The difference in treatment derives from a difference in wording.
The late R1749 (recall that the number was not what we believed it
to have been), or perhaps we should say the new R1764 (hooray!) states
that the casting of any votes may only be achieved by sending a message
to the Public Forum. This clearly makes it impossible to vote without
sending a message to the PF. R1729, however, does not say that voting
may only be achieved by sending a message to the Assessor. It says that
Players shall not vote in public. R1729 imposes a restriction on
Players which Players may break, like the Electioneering Rules, or
the Secrecy Rules. R1764 does not impose a restriction on Players in
the same sense.


